player.seasonOutlook: Adebayo has been metronome consistent for the past five seasons, notching within decimal points of his averages of 19.1 PPG, 9.7 RPG, 4.0 AGP, 1.2 SPG and 0.8 BPG every season. Last season he started playing more power forward to allow for dual-big lineups with Kel'el Ware, and this led to Adebayo setting a new career mark with a 3-pointer per game as well. Adebayo has played in 71 or more games in three straight seasons, and his consistent availability has allowed him to finish in the top-20 in total fantasy points even though he is only top-40 in fantasy points per game.

Aldama broke out last season with new career bests in five of the six fantasy hoops counting categories, excepting only blocked shots. He backs up every frontcourt position for the Grizzlies, but also gets spot starts in cases of injury. With Jaren Jackson Jr. questionable to start the season due to turf toe, Aldama could get some starts early on. Aldama is a stretch big with double-double potential and two 3-pointers per game when he gets minutes. He is a fringe top-100 fantasy hoops prospect with upside to deliver top-75 production when he moves into the starting lineup.

Allen is a walking double-double with low-teens scoring on almost 70% shooting from both the field and the line with about a block and a steal per game. He is very consistent, and has the upside to ramp up his scoring into the mid-upper teens if needed, but like the rest of the Cavaliers starters he played his fewest minutes last season since joining the team because the unit is so strong. Either way, what Allen does provide is worthy of early-mid round consideration in fantasy leagues.

Antetokounmpo remains on the short list of best fantasy producers in the NBA, coming off back-to-back seasons averaging over 30 points, 11.5 rebounds and 6.5 assists per game. Those numbers came largely with Damian Lillard as his point guard, but in 14 games without Lillard, Giannis averaged slightly more points (31.1 PPG) and almost a full 1.5 more assists (7.9 APG). With Lillard gone this season and shooting big man Myles Turner in the fold as another finisher, Antetokounmpo has even higher upside this season with an outside shot at flirting with a triple-double.

The Knicks return the same starting lineup this season as last, so we have a good idea what to expect from Anunoby. He is an elite 3-and-D wing, which translated to upper-teens scoring, more than two 3-pointers for the fifth-straight season and more than two combined steals + blocks for the sixth-straight season. Anunoby played a career-high 74 games last season after averaging 52 games in the four seasons before, so if he can replicate last season's availability he projects as a plus fantasy starter.

The Trail Blazers traded leading scorer Anfernee Simons and released fifth-leading-scorer Deandre Ayton this offseason, replacing both with more defensive-minded players. This really opens up the opportunity for Avdija and Shaedon Sharpe to be the leading offensive engines in the starting lineup. Avdija is coming off a breakout campaign in which he set or tied career-best marks in all six fantasy hoops counting categories for the season. He showed flashes of dominance last season, including averaging almost 27 points with 11 rebounds in his last 13 games, giving him upside to have another breakout campaign in 2025-26.

Ayton signed with the Lakers this offseason, and on-paper it looks like a perfect fit for his skill set. Ayton is a strong pick-and-roll finisher, and he gets to play with two elite pick-and-roll ball-handlers in Luka Doncic and LeBron James. Plus, the Lakers have a complete dearth of viable big man options besides Ayton. As a result, Ayton's scoring numbers could look more like his peak with the Suns when he averaged 17-18 PPG than his last couple relatively down seasons with the Trail Blazers. Ayton has averaged a double-double in every season of his NBA career, but that streak could be challenged playing in a lineup where both Doncic and James are excellent rebounders for their positions.

The rookie is set to make an immediate impact for the rebuilding Jazz. At 6-6, 200 pounds, he combines scoring, court vision and defensive versatility, able to drive, shoot and guard multiple positions. Bailey has a chance to emerge as Utah's second option behind Lauri Markkanen, contributing on both ends of the floor. Under Will Hardy's system and with veteran guidance, he has the tools to become a key scorer and playmaker as the Jazz look to develop their young core.

Ball is one of the most talented young guards in the NBA, an All-Star coming off averages of 25.2 PPG, 7.4 APG, 4.9 RPG and 3.8 3PG. His biggest issue is availability: in five NBA seasons, Ball has only played more than 51 games once. He has combined to play only 105 of a possible 246 games in the last three seasons. Ball is still only 24 years old and still getting better, but the Hornets have also brought in plenty of perimeter depth options this offseason to prepare in case he has availability issues again. Fantasy managers would be wise to do the same.

Banchero was the NBA Rookie of the Year in 2022-23, then improved across the board in his second season and seemed poised to take the league by storm in year 3 before injuries sidelined him for half the season. He still showed improvement as a shooter and scorer, getting up to 25.9 PPG and 1.9 3PG, but didn't make the leap that some expected. That expected explosion could be on tap for this season, though, with Banchero fully healthy and the addition of Desmond Bane on the wing. Bane is an elite, volume 3-point shooter that will force opposing defenses to respect his shot and open up the paint for Banchero and Franz Wagner to operate.

In his last few years with the Grizzlies, Bane developed into one of the better all-around shooter-scorer-playmakers on the wing in the NBA. He first showed he could be a primary scorer when injuries and suspension kept Ja Morant out of the lineup, but he has since proven he can produce even when in the lineup with other volume scorers. This will serve him well in Orlando, where he will be playing next to two strong offensive producers in the frontcourt in Paolo Banchero and Franz Wagner. Bane's ability to stretch the floor should open things up for Banchero and Wagner to create, while simultaneously their presence should get Bane more open looks. His efficiency could increase in Orlando, but his scoring volume is likely capped by his two talented teammates.
